\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid8419436 Jack Goody
\par Summary
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3742378 St John\rquote s College, Cambridge, 11-12 June 2008
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
\par Born Barnes 1919. Moved soon to Welwyn Garden City where brother Richard born.
\par 
\par Maternal grandfather had an extensive draper\rquote 
s shop in Turriff, Aberdeenshire, went recently to trace family history. Grandparents had 13 children, his mother the last. Bought large house in country, probably from speculations. Remembers grandmother from
 summer holidays, when cousins all came home. Paternal grandparents had died, grandfather commercial traveller, left seven children, brought up by \lquote aunt\rquote  who had been mother\rquote 
s help; Jack knew no London kin of this generation. Maternal grandmother not an influence; very Presbyterian, remembers her playing the harmonium on Sundays.
\par 
\par Parents had no secondary education, but keen on it. Mother continued her Scottishness; worked for Post Office in London from 16 until married. Told grandchildren about the old house. Spent time on her sons\rquote 
 education. Both parents keen readers, especially father: classics of all ages. Little discussion with parents. Father had started as electrical apprentice; wartime, Flying Corps officer; post-war, advertising manager in electric
s. So practised in journalistic writing; would correct Jack\rquote s proofs. Politically he read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Daily Telegraph}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , mother read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 News Chronicle; }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Jack followed mother. Emotionally close to both of them. They corresponded regularly when he was a prisoner-of-war. Discipline }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12278526 was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 mild.
\par 
\par Fairly free life as boys. Welwyn Garden City just starting \endash  brother the first boy born there. Very Quakerish, lots of cultural activities. Bernard Shaw nearby. A source of Jack\rquote s interest in literature. Father acting Shakespeare. Third br
other had died very young. As brothers, Jack and Richard very close: played bridge together, climbed together, at same schools and St John\rquote s. Richard, scientist, went on to Harvard.
\par 
\par Schools the key influence intellectually. Welwyn Garden C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10166902 ity primary school not important, even}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  though good. Parents decided to send them as dayboys to St Albans School, private school. English teacher there an important influence, introduced Jack to Frank Leavis and }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Scrutiny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
. History teachers not inspiring. Brother influenced by science teacher who wrote textbooks. 
\par 
\par Jack got sizarship (minor scholarship) to St John\rquote s. Believes in students working while studying. Came up in 1938, Richard in 1939. Why chose Cambridge? Had visited earlier with mother. Did try elsewhere, but St John\rquote s accepted him. Richard}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10166902  more clever}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
. No scholarship to St Albans, but annual fee only \'a318. Many school friends, but few important in long run. Of other locals, Ernest Gellner was at a county school; Colin Renfrew at same one.
\par 
\par Supported at Cambridge by St John\rquote s, St Albans School, and Hertfordshire County. St John\rquote 
s reputation then puritanical; Wordsworth and Wilberforce connections; drew many students from north. Cripps, a major benefactor, was son of northern scrap metal merchant. One master at St Albans, also northerner, had been a senior wrangler at St John
\rquote s. At one time recently five fellows came from St Albans.
\par 
\par St Albans School hall had board listing usually one Oxbridge scholarship a year, but exceptional group in Jack\rquote s year. Some were friends in Cambridge, others went to Oxford.
\par 
\par At Cambridge most influential teachers Leavis and his acolytes. Supervisor in St John\rquote s important: Hugh Sykes Davis, involved in surrealism, also Marxist, once suspected spy, Apostle. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140\charrsid3027847 John Cornford}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140  (a father of a friend James}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140\charrsid11891140  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140\charrsid3027847 Cornford}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140 )}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140\charrsid3027847  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140 was c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 oncern}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140 ed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  with Spanish Civil War}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140 , b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 ut }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11891140 Jack }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 did not consider going as also inclined to pacifism. Caithness friend of mother, 
\lquote aunt\rquote , was follower of Gandhi and vegetarian; much impressed by her. Doubts resolved by Guernica.
\par 
\par Mother churchgoer, low Anglican. Jack sent to Sunday school. Father not keen. After 14, religion not important to Jack. School friends not believers.
\par 
\par Joined CUSC (Cambridge University Socialist Club), where met friend Eric Hobsbawm, a big figure in club, \lquote a leader of men\rquote . Two years ahead, Eric had big collection of jazz records, \lquote very continental\rquote 
, knew about life in Paris, Vienna, Berlin, where had connections. Contrast with exclusive Englishness of Leavis school. With Eric, Arnold Kettle (lat
er at Leeds), George Scurfield (roommate, later Labour candidate) went to Paris for 14 July 1939 celebrations; then hitchhiked south, camped, first saw Mediterranean. 
\par 
\par Met E.P. (Edward) Thompson later, historian devoted to English tradition; Eric had a wi
der view. Also met Raymond Williams post-war. Other post-war friends included Ian Watt, with whom went to see Little Gidding in snow. Also George Scurfield, who had been in Burma, wrote a novel about it, tried to live as a writer, supported Raymond. Perha
ps met Raymond through adult education, or Army Bureau of Current Affairs, run by Cambridge Leavisite Boris Ford: ABCA led some friends into adult education, including George, Edward and Raymond.
\par 
\par Jack worked 1947-1949 in further education in Hertfordshire, living in Barnet with his wife and son. Organising and teaching classes in domestic skills. Raymond and Edward worked at higher level, university extra-mural. Remembers one drama class whose mem
bers could not read. Then decided to return to academic life.
\par 
\par Interested in Tavistock Institute of Human Relations, who kept an eye on ex-prisoners-of-war. Read article in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Pilot Papers }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 by Edward Shils on American social science. Wrote to him, very encouraging reply. Applied for post as researcher on Devon village, which W.M. Williams got.

\par 
\par So decided to do Ph.D. instead. Colonial Office scholarship. Had been very disappointed by Cambridge anthropology, except for visiting lectures by Evans-Pritchard, visiti
ng from Oxford. On scholarship, a year at Balliol, Oxford. Met Norman Birnbaum, Mel Richter and other sociologists.
\par 
\par In August 1939 was climbing with brother in Scotland, when heard war had broken out. Hitchhiked home to St Albans and joined ARP (Air Raid 
Protection). Returned to Cambridge, where arts graduates were being called up. Joined Cambridge University Training Corps, chosen for Sandhurst with very intellectual friend Matthew Hodgart (went high up in Intelligence) and met Chris (Dominic) Rieu, all 
s
ocialists, but already dissatisfied with Communist line on the war. Volunteered before being called up. Wanted to join infantry. Had been in Officers Training Corps at school. Had joined Communist Party six months earlier, but was very much against Ribben
trop pact. 
\par 
\par From Sandhurst sent to join Sherwood Foresters First Battalion stationed in Haifa, but ship unable to leave Liverpool due to Mediterranean blockade. Looked after French prisoners-of-war in Liverpool. Sent to Overstrand in East Anglia, guarding 
coast with First World War machine gun. Finally by ship Liverpool to Egypt via South Africa, and then to Cyprus. Regiment had been struggling, attacked by both Jews and Arabs in Palestine; then defending Cyprus. Before the war whole of eastern Mediterrane
a
n defended by regiment of 700 men. Instructed to take tennis racquet and lounge suit. New friends Frank Fisher (father later Archbishop of Canterbury) and David Smith-Dorrien (father a General in First World War). Regiment included many miners, and also u
nemployed.
\par 
\par Transferred to Egypt, relieved by whole Division, camped near pyramids. Fighting in desert mobile, little shooting. Disliked aerial bombardments.
\par 
\par Captured in Tobruk, June 1942. Taken to Benghazi, flown to Italy. Prison camp briefly in Bari, then camp at Chieti near Pescara \endash 
 now police training camp. Courtyard of brick huts. Camp held junior officers. Regime easy, just daily roll call, officers not made to work (unlike other ranks). Spent time on educational programme (took psychology, taught mo
dern poetry), theatre (classical and modern) and music. Had one musician (Anthony Baines?) who wrote down scores off gramophone records. Not enough books, no library. Impressed by all this cultural activity. Prisoners mainly from same regiment and social 
group.
\par 
\par Escaped for six months. Came across other cultures in Cyprus but especially living with Italian villagers as escapee. Escaped for first time October 1943 after Italian armistice. Germans put them on train for Germany. Jumped train with Frank Fisher,
 David Smith-Dorrien and Edmund Pickworth. Lived in a cave for a while, helped by villagers. Split in pairs, Jack with Frank, hoping to rejoin Allies at Monte Cassino. Recaptured, Frank got away, Jack not. Sent off by cattle train, attacked from air, esca
p
ed a second time through river. Went to Rome, but hope of Vatican asylum failed. Decided to walk north, footsore, hid in cave, fed by staff of rich American woman married to a Colonna. Returned to hiding in Rome, where recaptured and sent to Germany. Unco
mfortable time under Allied bombers. Has published account in Italian (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Oltre i Muri: La Mia Prigionia in Italia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , 1997), which he started writing in Germany. 
\par 
\par Was also learning Russian. Eichst\'e4tt prisoner-of-war camp had excellent library. Some prisoners had been getting books sent to them throughout the war. Jack read James Frazer\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Golden Bough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
, related to literature, mentioned by T. S. Eliot. Also Gordon Childe, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 What Happened in History, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 helped}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 to make sense of Middle East. Remembers in Cyprus Museum seeing bullock and plough from 3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 rd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 millennium BC, and still in use today: impressed by continuities, and how very early inventions still affect recent societies.
\par 
\par In becoming an anthropologist, these books important; also contact with other cultures in Cyprus 
and Italy. Also interest in social conflict. Tavistock Institute of Human Relations; Edward Shils article. At this preliminary stage, not influenced by contact with any anthropologists.
\par 
\par Returned to Cambridge 1945 (BA 1946; Diploma in Anthropology 1947). H
ad to read anthropology because no sociology. Anthropologists not interested in European studies before Julian Pitt-Rivers and others started work in Mediterranean. When Jack went to Oxford, he wanted to work on an Italian village, but told he must first 
study some other society. Hence he went to Africa \endash  and never got back!
\par 
\par Then no Cambridge teachers in anthropology, just Evans-Pritchard\rquote s visiting lectures. Meyer Fortes came later, which was why Jack and also Edmund Leach returned to Cambridge. Before th
at, just an American Swedish Lapp (Sami) specialist, and Reo Fortune. Taught with Godfrey Lienhardt (another Leavis pupil) by Glyn Daniel, who was an archaeologist. Godfrey went to teach in Oxford, Jack went into further education (for two years; then Col
o
nial Office Studentship to go to Oxford). Other students included John Barnes, sociologist; Emrys Peters, geographer, who wrote on Bedouin. Peter Worsley around (read English); Kathleen Gough (also read English, worked in India). Godfrey drew Jack towards
 Evans-Pritchard; but Ian Watt (in English) a stronger influence. 
\par 
\par Most leading anthropologists were not interested enough in history. L\'e9vi-Strauss writes of difference between bricolage and later thinking but never discusses mechanism of change. Evans-Pri
tchard a historian by training but the Nuer had no written history. Evans-Pritchard inspiring teacher; especially interesting on types of conflicts and conflict resolution among Nuer. Structural rather than historical approach to conflict interesting. But
 a radical reactionary: anti-authoritarian, but against the left. Meyer Fortes and Max Gluckman closer to left. Evans-Pritchard a Catholic conservative, continuing Oxford tradition of Radcliffe-Brown \endash  Oxford had a \lquote school\rquote 
 of anthropology, which Cambridge lacked. His pupils included Keith Thomas, Alan Macfarlane.
\par 
\par In Oxford (1949-1952) started work with Meyer Fortes. Chose him as supervisor because wanted to go somewhere nearer. Chose Ghana because less remote than say New Guinea; and because in Cambridge h
ad shared a room with Joe Reindorf, son of Ghana historian, later Attorney General. Travelled steerage, 12 days, so could return to see family mid-way, after one year.
\par 
\par Fortes very helpful, although did not always read manuscripts in detail. But Jack wrote easily, and didn\rquote t want much control. Started from Fortes\rquote  ideas on kinship, etc. Friends included Peter Worsley, Kathleen Gough, Cliff Slaughter (}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Coal Is Our Life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 ), al
l interested in kinship, then the talk of town. Now wonders why not more interest in religion, politics, etc.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5911747 Jack went to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 Ghana by ship. Sally Chilver, historian, in Colonial Office, allowed him to split costs and so return halfway by travelling steerage, warned by someone from shipping line that he would be sailing with \lquote black gentlemen\rquote 
. Included African law students; more interesting conversation than with Europeans on upper decks.
\par 
\par Met in Ghana by Kofi Busia, pupil of Fortes, who wrote on Ashanti, fol
lowed Nkrumah as Prime Minister, but then Head of Sociology in Legon (University of Ghana); looked after Jack. Got permits, kit and food quickly in Accra. Went to capital of Ashanti, Kumasi, where met administrator Peter Cannon, who also knew Fortes well.
 
Through his Colonial Office scholarship Jack was a Colonial Officer. Peter fixed a lorry for him and a cook steward from the Upper Volta area, with whom travelled north. On the way stayed in very large government rest house, where District Commissioner sh
o
t guinea fowl for supper. At next rest house District Commissioner, whose sister was married to Cambridge archaeologist, had huge gramophone. Finally next day reached research area but again stayed in government rest house, of mud and grass, before moved 
to village. Got to know local headmaster, Kunyamini Bni, chief\rquote s son, who told Jack much about the area, and helped him choose Birifu as village to settle in.
\par 
\par Fortes had worked in strictly patrilineal society, Jack wanted something different, and knew this area was partly matrilineal, from survey by District Commissioner Rattray. But once there, did not find fixed terminology for peoples.  \lquote Lobi\rquote 
 were matri}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5911747 lineal, others were \lquote Dagarti\rquote , but it wasn\rquote t fixed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 .  
\par 
\par Kit taken in lorry included camp bed, bath, pre
ssure lamp, food and beer. In village again started in rest house, built by locals; later lived in local house. Thick mud walls, flat roofs, no windows. Ate on roof; used tent for office. Never cooked himself. Cook/steward fetched water from river, choppe
d firewood from woods, went to market \endash  could not have combined this with fieldwork. Some Quaker visitors did try to do without servants but it was a burden on their wives.
\par 
\par For participant observation usually went with local man who could check the languag
e, but would also go out on his own and take a local beer. Learnt language on arriving. Most difficult to learn religious concepts. Went often to funerals, a good time to talk about inheritance, quarrels, etc, in natural way \endash 
 lasted three days. Could visit people and drink with them at home. Different houses brewed beer every day, easy to join, like a pub \endash  conversation \lquote completely natural\rquote .
\par 
\par Could observe women\rquote s roles. They also drank beer, might share a calabash with you, drinking one on each side. Not 
a Muslim area, could see women in kitchen or fields. Talking to women could be a moral problem, but as a foreigner had more leeway; local men couldn\rquote t walk into kitchen. But it was said to create difficulty if anthropologist took a lover. 
\par 
\par In African village, no privacy. If you hide, you may be accused of witchcraft. Would always write fieldnotes in privacy, ten pages a day. Problems with understanding complex concepts, which needed to be able to discuss later with a local.
\par 
\par Book most proud of is translation of Bagre myth (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 The Myth of the Bagre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , 1972), with SWDK (\'93Kum\'94
) Gandah, from the village. Worked together in London every weekend. Helped understand learning process and degree of variation in versions. Made him question L\'e9vi-Strauss\rquote  interpretations of myths as standardised, which meant that people
\rquote s creativity underestimated. First recorded by hand, later with tape recorder \endash  which brought out the variations. BBC flew out heavy old German tape recorder for broadcast. But when portable recorders came, re
turned many times with Kum to ceremonies in the same places. Locals now recording prayers etc. Longer recitations vary more. Benima Dagarti first told Jack about the myth and recited it. The first version took ten days, recorded versions shorter. Myth is 
secret, available only to initiates, so had to be in another room for recording.
\par 
\par Started initiation himself, some sacrifices, but decided not to sit naked in silence for two weeks. Becoming one of the group might have led to secrecy, as with Kenneth Little in Sierra Leone. 
\par 
\par Did join local political party, Convention People\rquote s Party, led by Nkrumah, and supported independence, but not a political activist. Did not feel neutrality would have made a difference, and useful to attend political meetings. You need
 to be somewhat involved to learn anything. Useful to show support, unless the situation is divisive. Should be open about which side you are on.
\par 
\par Fieldwork with LoWiili August 1950-September 1951. Returned March-December 1952 to study LoDagaba. Similar, but some differences in inheritance: LoWiili patrilineal, while LoDagaba inherited movable property in maternal line (e.g. to sister\rquote 
s son). LoDagaba also more Christian: hoped to learn more about Bagre, but didn\rquote t \endash  except to improve translation, which was
 easier to show to people in Christian area. Change of plan following first fieldwork. Wanted to understand whether LoWiili had switched away from matrilineal systems, and how marriage worked in these systems and between them.
\par 
\par Local support from Gerard Ch
arles, married to sister of a Cambridge archaeologist, and Guy Dyer Ball, ex-Oxford and army: both local Commissioners, helpful and hospitable. Close friends made in Ghana: Joe Reindorf; Benima Dagarti; brother of Kum, ran a hotel; Aloysius Denkabe, lectu
r
er at Legon (University of Ghana); local chief; xylophone player and his son; social welfare officer; Christine Oppong, professor in Ghana, who married a Ghanaian, has a flat in Cambridge, sees often. Also friends at university; taught there for a year wh
en Norbert Elias was there.
\par 
\par Revisited Ghana regularly. Second wife Esther Goody came on second fieldwork (c. 1955-1956); two years together working on Gonja, which became her thesis. Jack did historical work which he has not used. Based at Institute of Afr
ican Studies at Legon run by Thomas Hodgkin. Later, invited back to mark papers; also recording Bagre. More recently, went with Juliet to a conference, but did not go north. It is hard to find your way around Africa climbing onto lorries, in contrast to b
eing ferried around in colonial days.
\par 
\par Kum studied statistics as well as the Bagre. Most of family still hoe farming, back-breaking. With plough, can cultivate more land: leads to demand for land, stratification, division between literate and non-literate. These divisions now sharper in Ghana.
 Only literate get elected to Parliament. Markets little changed. European countries were similarly divided by literacy until late 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 th}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  century.
\par 
\par First wife Joan Wright, married in Cambridge (1946). Had been to Bedales, wrote thesis on A.S. Neill, strong interest in education. Had three children. Marriage got into difficulties when Jack went to Ghana for fieldwork.
\par 
\par Second wife Esther Newcomb, married c. 1955. American: sociologist, then anthropologist; father soc}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5911747 ial psychologist. Two children.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Is working in Ghana now.
\par 
\par Third wife Juliet Mitchell, married c. 2000, psychoanalyst writer on gender.
\par 
\par Do the children\rquote s interests show his influence? Jack\rquote s interest in Asian cultures has never been transcendental.
\par 
\par Edmund Leach an important colleague, learnt about L\'e9vi-Strauss, but neither he nor Fortes was interested in literacy or history. Nor, in contrast to France, were students interested in these themes. People are too stuck in their own patches.
\par 
\par Never felt the Ghanaians he knew lacked intelligence, but literacy brought tremendous changes in opportunities for learning. Difficulties of farmers in dealing with writing. But to do with communication, not with mentalities. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 The Domestication of the Savage Mind}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 was an ironic title, and for the French translation (Bourdieu) it was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8221423  changed to avoid offending}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  L\'e9vi-Strauss.
\par 
\par Audrey Richards, pupil of Malinowski, close to him, came to Cambridge with Meyer Fortes\rquote  disapproval, but Jack welcomed her. She started the African Studies Centre in Cambridge. Fortes again disapprov
ed, thought that social anthropology should be universal. Jack supported her and succeeded her as director. At same time got Smuts Readership. Went together to Elmdon, where Marilyn Strathern worked for Audrey on kinship and domestic organisation. Audrey 
had cottage in Elmdon. One of few interested in urban anthropology, unlike Fortes or Edmund Leach. Jack\rquote s student Keith Hart worked on changing systems in urban Accra.
\par 
\par Daryll Forde at UCL, very vigorous, wide interests, ran International African Institute with journal }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Africa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , interested Jack in comparative work. Studied Nigerian society which also had double descent system. Liked him, vigour and verve.
\par 
\par David Schneider, visited LSE, didn\rquote t know well. Worked with Jack\rquote s friend Kathleen Gough from Bradford who also worked on matrilineal systems. Book on kinship in South India, historical Marxist.
\par 
\par Knew Clifford Geertz, always interesting, thought his approach to anthropology \lquote a bit literary\rquote . Better on Indonesia than Morocco.
\par 
\par Raymond T. Smith knew closely, as graduate students in Cambridge shared house when both divorcing. Talked a lot about Caribbean kinship. Smith also went to Ghana, ended in Chicago. Through him met many famous West Indians.
\par 
\par Met Talcott Parsons, Geor
ge Homans and William Lloyd Warner in Cambridge, brought over to validate new chair in sociology. Fortes wanted Jack to do B. Litt (1952) for Oxford. While there, met political scientist from Harvard with literary background, Mel Richter, would meet for w
e
ekly cafe lunch to discuss a chapter of Parsons at a time. Esther wrote BA thesis on Parsons. Got to know Parsons in Cambridge. Jack wanted to integrate psychological with social, but Juliet would say he has not; Jack did read Freud for his thesis on mour
ning customs. Tensions and ambivalence over inheritance; how Gonja succession systems affected people\rquote s view of the deceased. But psychologists would not see this as psychological.
\par 
\par George Homans and Marc Bloch (through their books) started Jack\rquote s interest in the middle ages. Lloyd Warner also stimulating; stayed with him and Parsons in America. In Paris, Clemens Heller. Liked Bourdieu\rquote 
s analysis of gift and marriage systems in North Africa. Knew him when at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 \'c9cole des Hautes \'c9tudes en Science Sociale}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , then r
un by Heller. Jack had one of his books translated by Cambridge University Press. Personally sympathetic. But did not find his ideas on intellectual capital profitable: idea of cultural capital too loose. Extraordinary influence.
\par 
\par John Fage didn\rquote t know well, but visited in Legon when professor of history; later ran West African Centre in Birmingham.
\par 
\par General attitude to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid399459 methods}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 eclectic. In Ghana fieldwork in villages but also worked on historical records (both are in St John\rquote s library) and a loca
l household survey. Came up against problem of inaccuracy of information which people may give about their lives, for example, number of marriages.
\par 
\par Interest in comparative work began with north Ghana (1950-1952); then comparison of oral and literate socie
ties led to work on Europe. Influence of Ian Watt, also ex-prisoner-of-war, in Burma; and of Queenie Leavis. Article (1963) with Watt underestimates importance of other early forms of writing. Comparisons of inheritance, bridewealth and dowry systems. Ret
urned to Ghana with Esther 1955-1956 to work on the Gonja, a centralised system. On return started systematic comparative work using Murdoch\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Ethnographic Atlas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
, relating bridewealth and dowry systems to demography. This was then very unfashionable because of British emphasis on fieldwork. Jack collected comparative demographic material on family size and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10359208 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 stopping rules}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10359208 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 : dowry systems tend to reduce family size because of need for resources.
\par 
\par Methods depend partly on topic. Renaissances. Different versions of Bagre. Memory imperfect; critical of Vansina, prefers approach of Bartlett\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Remembering}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
. But hard to see variations in oral cultures before tape recorder. Sceptical of Vansina\rquote s school of African history based on oral tradition, but dynastic memories credible \endash 
 recorded some himself in Ashanti, and tried with Gonja. Recorded a drum history, but interpretations of these by two people very different. Need to give more credit to creativity in oral cultures. Otherwise, how are there some 8,000 cultural gr
oups in Africa? Cultures varied like English spoken in Britain.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid10359208 \lquote Unity of social sciences?\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  Influenced by Chicago work for a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
Unified Encyclopaedia of the Social Sciences}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , never published, which included Thomas Kuhn on revolutions. Little advantage in divi
sion between anthropology and sociology \endash  against \lquote institutionalised boundaries\rquote 
. Some practical rationale for division between student of village and of factory, but no intellectual rationale. Should be looking for links. Hence favoured starting Social an
d Political Sciences in Cambridge. Post-war, few universities offered either anthropology or sociology. Difficult to get universities to change. Anthropology came for practical purposes. Struggle to establish sociology in Cambridge.
\par 
\par Distrusts }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10359208 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid10359208 binary contrasts}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10359208 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , as in work of L\'e9
vi-Strauss: overblown, made key to understanding. In England taken up especially by Rodney Needham in Oxford. Partially correct, but trivial. Doesn\rquote t allow for ambiguities. A xylophone player uses his left hand most, but was he real
ly seen as female? Was black just associated with women or witchcraft - could also signify beauty or rain? Similarly, no absolute contrast between literate and oral cultures: reading modified rather than ended orality.  L\'e9
vi-Strauss looked at contrasts, but not how one can move from one into the other. Fortunately this approach now unfashionable.
\par 
\par Social divisions introduced by the plough, had just come in when Jack came to Northern Ghana. When the first man got a plough through missionaries, he would ploug
h the common pastures, and claim more land. So could see the change happening. Contrast between African hoe and Eurasian plough culture in shaping stratification. Gordon Childe on the Bronze Age was important.
\par 
\par Detailed descriptions of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3565120 productive systems}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  in early books, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Social Organisation of the LoWiili }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 (1956) and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
Technology, Tradition and the State in Africa }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
(1971). Not enough attention in Marxism to changes in agricultural productive systems or means of destruction or to the technology of the intellect (
e.g. writing). Later visited part of Northern Ghana where plough agriculture had come in for rice production to look at legal disputes on land tenure. Importance of written claims to land for courts. These insights always present in later work. Influence 
of Fernand Braudel, raising other problems.
\par 
\par Theme of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3565120 social and political control}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Succession to High Office}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
, ed. 1966). Struck by quasi-anarchic LoDagaba, social control without an authoritarian government \endash  although recognised there were limits. Radcliff
e-Brown had been sympathetic to anarchism, admired Kropotkin. Local societies did produce men who became chiefs. Friend Kum, with whom edited book; his father a chief, appointed by government. Kum therefore sent to school, came to England, became}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3565120  a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  statist
ician. But before that, no formal chiefships, no institution.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3565120 Inheritance:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 interested that unlike in Europe, in Africa even when inheritance matrilineal, was through a woman to a man, e.g. to a sister\rquote s son. In Europe women didn\rquote 
t necessarily inherit, but at marriage they were endowed, given their portion, or could inherit a crown. In Africa they could always find a male cousin to inherit. In Europe a woman could inherit the property and bring in a man to marry (e.g. Prince Phili
p
) but not in Africa. This related to relatively open marriage in Africa where fewer social differences, while choice mattered much more in Europe and Asia. In Africa no full matrilineal descent, so women not important in own right for male property. In an
cient Greece a woman had to marry a cousin to keep property in the family: having property led to more control of women. Must distinguish matrilineal societies from matriarchal societies in which women have real power. Article by Audrey Richards in }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 African Systems of Kinship and Marriage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 . Dowries belong to women, and usually return to them after divorce. Even in Islamic societies: Jack has Iranian }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3565120 female}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 friend who has recovered dowry through several divorces. By contrast in Africa father does not give to daughter; at marriage, bridewealth goes out but to other males. Women\rquote s participation in markets important \endash 
 they supported Nkrumah: trading in local food, clothing and beer, but not big traders. Long distance trade in hands of men.
\par 
\par This interest goes back as ethnography to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Death, Property and the Ancestors }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 (1962) and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Production and Reproduction }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 (1976). Then switched to historical work on early mediaeval Europe in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Development of the Family and Marriage in Europe }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
(1983). Not happy with accounts of Anglo-Saxon
 kinship, described as more patrilineal than it was. Also, what was the influence of French kinship terms, all bilateral, on Anglo-Saxon? Also, why did most early mediaeval wills leave property to the church? Needed to formalise the transfer through writt
en documentation. Amazing that by 800 AD one third of arable land in Europe in church hands. How had inheritance system changed to make that possible? Laws eventually to restrict this, and switch to endowing masses. 
\par 
\par On}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid6233885  literacy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , four books: }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Literacy in Traditional Societies }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
(ed. with Ian Watt, 1968); }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 The Domestication of the Savage Mind }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 (1977); }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 The Logic of Writing and the Organisation of Society }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 (1986); }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
The Interface Between the Written and the Oral }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 (1987). }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6161392 \'93I went to town on that!\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  Interest goes back ver
y early; influence of Ian Watt. Later felt work too European in perspective, became interested in different forms of writing. Earlier influence by work of Eric Havelock at Harvard, who got away from the idea of Greek \lquote spirit\rquote 
. But ignored fact that not only Greeks but also Phoenicians, Jews, Indians had alphabets. Had been thinking too much on evolutionary lines, of alphabetic script \lquote emerging\rquote 
 from earlier scripts. Impressive role of Chinese logographic script in holding together a vast empire, keeping local cultures, rather than imposing a single language as in USA. Told at talk in Japan that universal characters were the way of the future.

\par 
\par Important to shift emphasis from modes of production to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid6161392 modes of communication}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 . This is one reason for Jack\rquote s current interest in Renaissances. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid6161392 
Modes of destruction}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  are also important \endash 
 armies, the invention of gunpowder. Saw raids by Gonja horsemen on LoDagaba, like mediaeval feudal knights. Group of raiders, who inherited, made a much wider controlling social group. Led to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Succession to High Office }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
(ed. 1957). They succeeded by rotational succession.
\par 
\par When originally in Ghana, literacy was spreading. Kum one of the first local boys to go to school. He resented being shut up in classroom while other boys roamed the fields. New school also in Jack\rquote 
s village. At funerals, one of the schoolboys would write a list of gifts, which had previously been remembered orally, so that by next funeral it would only be partly remembered. Once there is a list, you act from that, rather 
than considering your relationships first. Local Improvement Society set up, keeping records of meetings, so at next meeting the minutes of previous were considered: an impulse for change.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid4681706 Cuisine:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Cooking, Cuisine and Class }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 (1982); }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Food and Love}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 (1998). Interest began with concern that social researchers were misunderstanding cultural differences between Eurasia and Africa. Felt he had been wrong about different kinds of writing in Eurasia, which could do many of the same things. How else could 
you explain the richness of Chinese science and culture as depicted by Joseph Needham? Marx and Weber had underestimated the East.
\par 
\par Little major difference between food in Europe and Asia, both elaborate cuisines. Stimulated by article by L\'e9vi-Strauss, whic
h ignored presence of plough or writing. Food in Eurasia depended on social specialisation made possible by plough and the records made possible by writing. Contrast with Africa, where had observed food, unvarying, porridge and soup. Same food in chief
\rquote s h
ouse, just more of it; possibly more meat. Elaborate food in Asia for merchants, this also now developing in North Africa. In Europe and Asia stratification of food. Sees this as going back to Bronze Age. Economies of Europe and the East were then very cl
ose, and subsequently, and China and India re-emerging now.
\par 
\par Doubted that French troubadours invented love, as Europeans maintain. Love poetry of Ovid, and in Muslim culture, influencing Andalusia and Sicily. Europe not unique. Economic changes more important than Weber\rquote 
s ethical ones, which can be found in other societies, including Taliban. Does not accept contrasts between European and Asian cities, or science. Led to writing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 The Theft of History}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 (2006): Europe claims too much, a racist historiography, which ignores Chinese achievements, and the European Holocaust.  L\'e9
vi-Strauss argued Chinese and Australian Aboriginal kinship variations of same system, but Chinese marriage system is much closer to Europe: in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
The Oriental, the Ancient and the Primitive: Systems of Marriage and the Family in the Pre-Industrial Societies of Eurasia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 (1990) argued against Peter Laslett and Cambridge Group view of special European marriage pattern. Late marriage does not explain population control, which was achieved by restraint within marriage in China. James Lee and Wang Feng in }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 One Quarter of Humanity}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 prove Malthus wrong: Laslett very Malthusian.
\par 
\par Less concerned by differences in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid4681706 cuisine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  within Far East. Preferred Chinese food to Japanese, which found }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4681706\charrsid3027847 
over-elaborate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
: soup with herb from Mount Fuji, served by geishas. Had lived in India, but did not experience Chinese and Japanese home foods until later.
\par 
\par More interested by stratification and marriage systems. In Africa, people marry as wish; in Europe and Asia, intermarry within the same class. Result in Africa many cross-cutting ties, because chief could have wives from different groups.
\par 
\par Didn\rquote t do fieldwork on food on his travels. Knows little about it practically! Does some cooking, including Indian and African foo
d. Went to Indonesia and Bali. Also to Australia, food very basic, best food in Chinatown. Sydney Aborigines very poor, brought up on missions where no cooking was done. Missionary food in Africa pretty basic (although in Africa French priests eat better)
. In African compound people cook in front of houses, few differences.
\par 
\par By }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Food and Love }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
means food and marrying, not sexuality. Demographers talk of freedom of choice as \lquote love marriage\rquote . But arranged marriages also common in Europe, and choice socially res
tricted; while in Africa, despite arranged marriages there was a possibility of choice, especially for second marriages. Not a sharp contrast between freedom and prescription. The link between form of marriage and capitalism is frail.
\par 
\par Discourse of love ra
rely found in Africa; elsewhere especially in writing, as in letters. Love poetry also usually to somebody at a distance: elaboration of discourse in writing follows. Not found in African oral culture. Describes how love expressed face to face in Africa. 
You don\rquote t need to have a discourse of love to have the feelings of love, but they interact. Some African love songs, but no letters or poems. Everything is validated face to face.
\par 
\par On }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 The Culture of Flowers }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
the basic issues were similar to cooking. Flowers 
not grown in Africa although there are wild flowers: no culture of flowers as in Europe and Asia. Some influence of Indian flowers. One flower has come across Sahara from North Africa. Junzo Kawada as a Japanese asked an Upper Volta chief where he was gro
wing flowers, was thought a mad question, you couldn\rquote t eat flowers. Not even fruit trees domesticated, whereas in Asia peach trees can be grown solely for New Year blossom display, as he saw in Hong Kong.
\par 
\par For one period even the West rejected flowers. The Romans had grown roses around graveyards. Protestants against flowers in graveyards, still are in Scotland and north-eastern USA. As Jack\rquote s mother put it, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4681706 \'93}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 I\rquote d rather ha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4681706 ve eggs\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 . Has changed now, but Jewish and Muslim graveyards are still without flowers. 
Because flowers suggest you are worshipping the dead.
\par 
\par Doesn\rquote t garden himself. His interest is in the idea of flowers rather than the flowers themselves. Shifting meanings: gave Chinese secretary who was leaving yellow chrysanthemums for long life, but Italian friend appalled, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4681706 \'93}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 They are the flowers of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4681706  the dead\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
. Chrysanthemums had come from China to France c. 1790, became a flower for All Saints/Souls Day. In Paris market, sold out of season as daisies. Interested by changing symbolism of flowers.
\par 
\par Secret language of flowers relates to this, but also to issue of literacy. Every flower had a special meaning. In 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  century England could make up a bouquet conveying a specific message. Typical of urban culture with writing.
\par 
\par Absence of aesthetic gardening in A
frica, although some missionaries grow flowers and there are now some flower sellers outside hospitals. Similar developments in India and Japan. In India cut flowers for garlands have no stems, flowers float in bowls rather than vases. In Japan plants usu
ally grown in pots.
\par 
\par New fieldwork on travels. Kept fieldnotes, now in St John\rquote s College library. Special journey to South China to see New Year and cutting of peach trees.
\par 
\par Visited American cemeteries. In East on All Saints Day, neither Protestants nor Catholics had flowers, except for a Polish grave, and they were obviously recent European migrants. Italian Catholic migrants had been criticised for processing with the image
 of Virgin, so much disapproved that dropped it; similarly with flowers. French and Italian cemeteries on All Saints Day full of flowers, with flower markets outside. Some in London too.
\par 
\par Had previously spent three months in village near Ahmedabad, because he felt he needed to know more about India. Arranged by family of old St John\rquote 
s friend, physicist. Returned to look at flower markets, to see where flowers for garlands produced. His farewell seminar at Cambridge was on flowers, and two friends wove him a garland for this; son bought another garland for his 80}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  birthday.
\par 
\par Went to China for first time to find out about flowers. Went to Japan for six months to Museum of Ethnology at Osaka, surrounded by gardens, did research there. Found Japanese culture dif
ficult and different. High degree of refinement in food. Met expert in Japanese food to watch cutting live fish for sushi.
\par 
\par Historic craftsmanship of Japan, kimonos, knives, very advanced, facilitated shift to industrial production. Similarly with China, which up to the early 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  century had been the world\rquote 
s biggest exporter, now picking up again. Module production with division of labour, as terracotta army. Marx and Weber wrong in seeing early division between East and West. Not just the East taking from the West; the West took china, silk, printing }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15690762\charrsid3027847 etc.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  from the East.
\par 
\par Did more ethnography for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Culture of Flowers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 , hence a longer book. Observation in North and South America: flower market in S\'e3o Paulo. First book after retirement so could work on it fullti
me; earlier books written while teaching. Started with African-Eurasian contrast but then explored Asian diversity. Manuscript longer than published book, included chapter on Japan, published in French translation, but cut by Cambridge University Press. S
upported by fellowships at Yale (Whitney Centre) and in California (Getty Centre).
\par 
\par Visit to India 1977. Most of Jack\rquote s contemporaries only did comparative work in Africa, as he did on Gonja political systems, although published little from this. Archival w
ork in PRO (Public Record Office) and Ghana. But did not find a major thread to develop. Instead, began working on contrasts with Eurasia. Not convinced that caste and class are so very different: with both, in-marriage in a circle contrasts with open mar
riage in Africa (exogamy).
\par 
\par Wanted to stay in a village to understand Asia better. Village chosen, near  Ahmedabad, turned out to be a town of 4,000 people. In Africa, a village would number only 400, so just use bush for sanitation; in India rules needed. 
Chose village through friends, Sarabhai family, Jains, cotton millers; he was a scientist who had been at St John\rquote 
s; wife a fantastic dancer. Jains an educated and liberal caste and religion, gave support to Gandhi, heavily involved in industry. Went for a summer vacation, instead of usual visit to Africa. Lived in schoolteacher\rquote 
s house in high caste section which made for difficulties in who could visit. Caste important in everyday life. Incident when Congress headman invited lower caste weavers whom Jack 
wanted to interview: they were deliberately served tea in broken cups. A Congress village, yet untouchables forced to use a different well. 
\par 
\par Had a translator, whose family had been in East Africa, very helpful, took Jack round. But also able to converse s
omewhat in English. Interested in processes of making cloth, growing indigo and dyeing. Never really wrote this up. Had woman as cook. Not able to eat meat or eggs, had to follow Brahmin rules. Difficult to visit the untouchables, but not with the farming
 majority, Patels. Untouchables commuted to work in  Ahmedabad, which opened them to modern world. In village found person who was aware of Sanskrit roots of words.
\par 
\par Taught in Cambridge 1954-1984, after Meyer Fortes became professor. Before that, anthropolo
gy teaching haphazard. Fortes wanted to teach social structure, economy and kinship systematically. Jack originally lectured on politics and law, had to read up primitive law. Later able to choose to lecture on religion, and eventually on kinship \endash 
 the high status topic, mainly taken by Fortes and Leach. Didn\rquote 
t lecture on his later research topics as a main theme. Never had a student working on literacy: they wanted to do traditional fieldwork. Even those who went to India or China did not look at the writt
en languages, or know them. In India he had wanted to see how the oral and written came together in a local context, and how Sanskrit tradition was handed down. But could not teach this kind of theme, had to teach face-to-face interaction.
\par 
\par As professor (1
973) arranged pre-fieldwork courses, including techniques of language learning and keeping fieldwork records. Jack himself kept fieldnotes, diary and household census over time. Belief in credibility of census shaken when long term interviewee subsequentl
y
 mentioned an additional marriage. Problems in how to follow and understand responses. Students not taught interview techniques, assumed skills would come naturally, and would vary depending on where you were going. You went to look for the problems. Nobo
dy had known enough about his Ghana villages to give him much advice. But he did introduce a course on fieldwork methods.
\par 
\par Director of African Studies Centre, 1966-1973, an independent unit of which Fortes did not approve. Succeed Audrey Richards from LSE, 
who favoured regional studies, while Fortes thought anthropology should be a universal subject, like economics. (Failure to recognise difference in context is why economics has not worked in Africa.) Fortes and Evans-Pritchard refused to join African Stud
ies Association. Anthropology had concentrated on Africa because funds available for research there. Jack\rquote s seminar published as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
Literacy in Traditional Societies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  (ed. 1968) was run from African Studies, would have been impossible from Department of Anthropology.
\par In post-war period anthropologists in India and China worked simply on oral culture, as in Africa. Jack had wanted to do fieldwork in Europe, but got no support: told he must first go to Africa.
\par 
\par As Director of African Studies Jack ran joint seminar with sociologist Edward Shils, interdisciplinary, and about any world region. Had difficulty in publishing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Literacy in Traditional Societies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
 because Cambridge University Press uncertain which discipline it related to. Not a large number of Ph.D. students.
 Those important to Jack included Francesca Bray, Sinologist, professor at Edinburgh; Martha Mundy, Arabic studies, professor at LSE; Keith Hart, went to West Africa, Goldsmiths. Chris Hann, now Director Max Planck Institute for Social Anthropology, did v
i
llage studies in Hungary and Poland, tea plantation in Turkey, China. Some Ph.D. students went into sociology, including Jeremy Tunstall, Hull fishermen; Vanessa Maher, Moroccan kinship, now Verona. Jack, now retired, does not miss lecturing, but enjoys g
iving seminars: recently in France. 
\par 
\par Jack\rquote s new ideas mainly developed independently rather than through discussions in anthropological contexts. Did talk with Edward Shils. Ideas on Africa developed through writing. Thinking about East-West stimulated thr
ough battling with notions of the Cambridge Group. Longstanding influence of Marx and Weber, and more recently Perry Anderson. Ideas came mostly through reading rather than discourse. St John\rquote 
s has been a great boon but not important as place for discussing ideas. Not influenced by David Lockwood as fellow; more by Parsons, but had read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 The Structure of Social Action}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  before he came.
\par 
\par Particularly proud of fieldwork and of work on the Bagre, interpreting, and showing variations, and inventiveness in traditio
nal societies. Most influential work has been on literacy. Forthcoming book on Renaissances. Prediction of lesser difference between East and West is now being fulfilled. But Africa cannot build on its past in similar way.
\par 
\par Has been fortunate in academic life, but has had problems in personal life, partly because of fieldwork; came back from Africa to find his family situation changed. Cheered to produce a new book aged 89. Uncertain of best experience: perhaps election to c
hair, and first fieldwork, friendship with Kum: his death a great loss. As also Fortes, Edmund Leach, Peter Laslett, Raymond Williams. Especially enjoyed knowing historians like Eric Hobsbawm, E.P. Thompson, Rodney Hilton on boards of both }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Past and Present}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 Comparative Studies in Society and History}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3027847\charrsid3027847 
. As with African Studies, this got him out of narrow discipline. Such freedom is unusual in academic life.
\par 
